

Some 300 homes involving 2,000 people of Katunje-2 village in Nepali Dhading district have benefited from Solar Electrification Project (SEP).

With the total cost of 16 million Nepali rupees ( 228,571 US dollars ), the project was executed by Central Electronics Limited (CEL), a public undertaking of the Indian government in partnership with Nepali Alternative Energy Promotion Center, a semi-governmental organization, a press statement of Embassy of India reaching here said Tuesday.

The project involves the provision of a solar panel, a maintenance free battery and a home lighting system of 75 watts, as well as planning, implementation and maintenance.

So far, India has executed 10 solar electrification projects worth 160.7 million ruppes (2.29 million dollars) in various districts in Nepal.

